post_text:
This page is designed to provide information and updates to the CSAT community, and to celebrate the achievements of CSAT students, staff, and schools. We welcome comments and questions from visitors but expect users to be respectful and civil when posting. Comments may be removed if they contain the following:

• Vulgar language and profanity (including when letters are replaced with the * symbol)
• Material that is unlawful, obscene, defamatory, threatening, harassing, abusive, slanderous, hateful, or that constitutes a personal attack of any kind
• Material that promotes or constitutes discrimination in any form
• Commercial content, solicitations, and spam
• Statements not related to the original post or purpose of the page
• Content that violates copyright, the Facebook terms of service, and school policies
• Users who repeatedly post comments containing any of the above may be banned from the page.

Thank you for visiting and please contact us with any questions, comments or concerns you have regarding this page or these Comment Guidelines.

post_text:
The Charter School for Applied Technologies is pleased to announce that Anthony Favata has been named Middle School principal and Michele Fiorella has been named Middle School assistant principal.

Mr. Favata comes to CSAT with 16 years of experience in education. A Western New York native, he recently returned to the area from Broward County, Florida. There, he served the last six years as an assistant principal within the Broward County Public Schools, the sixth-largest school district in the nation. Favata holds a bachelor’s degree in education from Buffalo State College and a master’s degree in educational leadership from Florida Atlantic University.

Mrs. Fiorella has been with CSAT for 14 years, most recently serving as assistant director of special education. Previously, she served as a special education educator and mentor. Fiorella holds a bachelor’s degree in elementary education and a master’s degree in special education from D’Youville as well as advanced certification in school building leader and school district leader from Canisius College.
text:
The Charter School for Applied Technologies is pleased to announce that Anthony Favata has been named Middle School principal and Michele Fiorella has been named Middle School assistant principal.

Mr. Favata comes to CSAT with 16 years of experience in education. A Western New York native, he recently returned to the area from Broward County, Florida. There, he served the last six years as an assistant principal within the Broward County Public Schools, the sixth-largest school district in the nation. Favata holds a bachelor’s degree in education from Buffalo State College and a master’s degree in educational leadership from Florida Atlantic University.

Mrs. Fiorella has been with CSAT for 14 years, most recently serving as assistant director of special education. Previously, she served as a special education educator and mentor. Fiorella holds a bachelor’s degree in elementary education and a master’s degree in special education from D’Youville as well as advanced certification in school building leader and school district leader from Canisius College.

post_text:
Mark Mulville, Buffalo News photographer, recently embarked on a large-scale project to honor WNY High School Seniors, visiting almost 80 schools and photographing close to 350 students. CSAT is thrilled to be included in the BN Salute to Seniors which recognizes standouts who truly embody the spirit of high school.

Standouts from CSAT include: Calvin Brown (Science Olympiad); Edwin Williams (Leadership), Juan Brown (Athletics); Abigail Clayton (Music) and Elizabeth Thida Htway (Art).

The BN Salute to Seniors is set to start running in the print edition of the Buffalo News this Sunday, June 14 with additional picture page each day Tuesday, June 16 through Saturday, June 20. The entire gallery is available online here. Congrats to our Seniors! The sky is the limit!!!

CNN and "Sesame Street" will host a town hall meeting to talk to kids about racism, the recent nationwide protests, embracing diversity and being more empathetic and understanding. The 60-minute special, "Coming Together: Standing Up to Racism. A CNN/Sesame Street Town Hall for Kids and Families," will air tomorrow, June 6 at 10 a.m.

Click here for details: https://www.cnn.com/2020/06/02/us/cnn-sesame-street-standing-up-to-racism/index.html?fbclid=IwAR06v4wRki9HDH8khWmq0KKZ80aPgwzGIDkjhPXuTZQEEtPZFEUMkz-rSuw

To the CSAT Class of 2020: Senior Lawn signs have arrived! We hope you’ll place them in front of your home with pride to show the community you are on the brink of accomplishing something amazing.

Signs can be picked up at the Family Support Center on Thursday, May 14 and Friday, May 15 between 10 a.m. and 2 p.m. We ask that you pull up and open your trunk so we can place the sign in your vehicle. (We will be asking for student names, one per student please.)

Those who cannot pickup these days can obtain a sign at Cap & Gown pickup in June (information TBA).

Thank you and congratulations!

post_text: We are thrilled to announce that the NYS Education Department Board of Regents voted to issue CSAT a full-term five-year renewal at their May 4 meeting. This is the greatest allowable charter term in NYS and ensures that CSAT can continue to serve the educational needs of our community for years to come. We cannot express enough thanks to all of you for your continuous support of our school.
text: We are thrilled to announce that the NYS Education Department Board of Regents voted to issue CSAT a full-term five-year renewal at their May 4 meeting. This is the greatest allowable charter term in NYS and ensures that CSAT can continue to serve the educational needs of our community for years to come. We cannot express enough thanks to all of you for your continuous support of our school.

post_text:
To have some fun this week, we are challenging our K-12 students to the CSAT Quarantine Slam Dunk Challenge*. The object is to use anything you have to slam dunk a ball. It can be a basketball hoop, a hula hoop, a laundry basket, whatever you can come up with! When you figure it out, have a parent or adult get a short video clip of your slam dunk and share it with us. Visit our website for details: http://ow.ly/wMPQ50zcxlg

*Please be sure to maintain social distancing and BE SAFE!

post_text:
Dear CSAT Community-

I realize that there are many questions that parents and students have regarding everything from state assessments, AP Exams and graduation requirements, to new student registration, the lottery and everything in between. As a school, our main goal right now is to help families in this unprecedented situation and to ensure the CSAT community remains safe.

The New York State Education Department continues to provide guidance for schools as they work through these many questions. We will share relevant updates with you as soon as we are able.

I encourage you to continue checking our website for the most up-to-date information. As always, thank you for your patience and be safe.

Best, Andrew Lyle
Superintendent

post_text: Beginning tomorrow, March 17, CSAT will begin distribution of breakfast and lunch for students who may need them. Meals will be distributed at our Middle School at 24 Shoshone Street and our Elementary School at 2303 Kenmore Avenue. Families can go to either site between the hours of 11 a.m. and 1 p.m. regardless of which building their children are enrolled. Multiple meals can be picked up if at least one child in the home attends CSAT. Please have your child’s student identification number ready. Meals will be grab and go and cannot be consumed on site. Please continue visiting our website at csat-k12.org for the most up-to-date information.

post_text: In order to protect our students and the community, CSAT is adhering to the state and county regulations to cancel all large group gatherings due to concerns related to COVID-19. Therefore, effective immediately, we will be limiting student travel and cancelling all upcoming events including field trips, concerts and sporting events. Please visit our website for additional information including a list of events. As always, the health and safety of our students, staff and our community is our highest priority. Huge thanks to Cindy for sharing her talents and experience with our students!

post_text: The CSAT Class of 2020 wrapped up their Senior Experience yesterday with the Prepare to Fly event. Seniors had the option of attending their choice of sessions on a multitude of real-life issues and experiences, including time management, college life, meal prep and cooking, small home repairs, voting, finances, self-care and more. Thank you to all our volunteer presenters for making this event possible and to Bryant & Stratton College for hosting this event at their city campus.

post_text: Great job, Eagles!!
shared_text:
CSAT Eagle Bands
January 11 at 12:38 PM ·

ECMEA Jazz Ensemble auditions today with two awesome and talented HS students. Both played terrific and their high scores reflected that. Now we start prep for NYSSMA Jazz in May. Great job today ladies!

Also, shout out to Ms. Kij’s baritone player who also played and scored very well for his ECMEA Elementary Band audition!

3 soloists today leaving with smiles and high grades. Ms. Kij and Mr. Sibbitts are leaving proud and very happy with our results!

Go eagles! 🦅

#csat #csatband #ECMEA

post_text: CSAT has immediate openings for the 2019-2020 school year for Grades 9, 10 and 11 at our High School and Grade 6 at our Middle School. New students would begin at the start of the second semester (Tuesday, January 28, 2020.) Apply online at this link (https://www.csat-k12.org/Page/3246) or call (716) 710-3068 for more information.

post_text: High School chorus students, under the direction of Sara Martinez, recently returned from a field trip to Fox Run at Orchard Park. There, students performed their Winter Concert Program and sang carols for members of the Fox Run community. The groups were well received by both residents and staff. Great job, Eagles!
